<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38100h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38100h">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38100h"> 100(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> dyffryn</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Welsh Place-Names]</font> &mdash; <font color="green">[Nearly]</font> all parishes, villages, halmets, farms, houses, woods, fields, streams and valleys possess native appellations, which in most cases are descriptive of natural situation, <i>e.g. Nantyffin</i>, the boundary brook; <i>Aberporth</i>, mouth <font color="green">[Latin <i>os</i>]</font> of the harbour; <i>Talybont</i>, end of the bridge; <i>Troedyrhiw</i>, foot of the hill; <mark><i>Dyffryn</i>, a valley</mark>, &amp;c. <small> &ldquo;WALES&rdquo; <a name="EBWA" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EBWA"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) XXVIII 259</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
